context: There are <a0_0><b4_0><b9_0>three<b9_0/><b4_0/><a0_0/> main chemical pulping processes: the sulfite process dates back to the <a1_0><b10_0>1840s<b10_0/><a1_0/> and it was the dominant method extent before the second world war. <a2_0><b11_0>The kraft process<b11_0/><a2_0/>, invented in the 1870s and first used in the <b8_0>1890s<b8_0/>, is now the most commonly practiced strategy, one of its advantages is the chemical reaction with lignin, that produces heat, which can be used to run a generator. Most pulping operations using the kraft process are net contributors to the electricity grid or use the electricity to run an adjacent paper mill. Another advantage is that this process recovers and reuses all inorganic chemical reagents. <a3_0><b5_0><b6_0><b7_0><b12_0>Soda pulping<b12_0/><b7_0/><b6_0/><b5_0/><a3_0/> is another specialty process used to pulp straws, bagasse and hardwoods with high silicate content.
